    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-08-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-08-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="41"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d41">
                <head>41. Letter From the <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d41fn1">Source: Eisenhower Library, Whitman
                        File, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>–<persName
                            corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> Series.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-08-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 2, 1955</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. President</hi>: I attended, for a short time this
                    morning, the meeting at Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BET1"
                    >Benson</persName>’s office to discuss the cotton matter. Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HHCJ1">Hoover</persName> was with me and also Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_HG2">Humphrey</persName> and Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_WS1">Weeks</persName> were there.</p>
                <p>I tried to make clear that we in the State Department are working for the United
                    States just as much as is anybody else and that I did not like it when it was
                    intimated to Congress, as it so often is, that we were primarily concerned with
                    pleasing foreign interests.</p>
                <p>I said that if, for example, there was a projected cotton policy which would
                    gravely disrupt the economy of Mexico and which, because of its effect on
                    Pakistan and Egypt, would jeopardize the oil situation in the Middle East, then
                    I thought there was a duty to point that fact out. If it was decided
                    nevertheless to go ahead I would, of course, abide by that decision.</p>
                <p>In the present case the Agriculture Department policy was, as you know, opposed
                    by all of the other agencies represented on the <persName corresp="#p_DJM1"
                        >Dodge</persName> Committee. It was very strongly opposed by Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_HG2">Humphrey</persName> and Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_WS1">Weeks</persName>. However, it is convenient for the
                    Department of Agriculture people, at the lower level, to concentrate blame on
                    the State Department. I told Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BET1"
                        >Benson</persName> that I thought that ought to stop. He agrees but admits
                    that it is easier said than done.</p>
                <p>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_HG1">Hauge</persName> who was present will tell you
                    about the substance of the meeting.</p>
                <pb facs="0164" n="134" xml:id="pg_134"/>
                <p>I stopped in to see Senator <persName corresp="#p_GWF1">George</persName> at his
                    apartment last evening and we had quite a lengthy and very intimate talk.
                    Although our talk covered many things, he did not once mention cotton.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">JFD</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
